result.text:
Here's my thoughts and outline of the first full day with my @Humane Pin. I am also attaching a few pictures taken, and a screen shot showing the data from the day. The camera did struggle with bad overhead lighting, especially on faces, as you can see. The data page detail is mostly in monochrome digits, if that area is not highlighted. So if you look closely, you can see that I used the mic 51 times, made 7 phone calls, listened to 232 songs, and requested 15 translations. 

I had the Pin on me from 7:30 am - 10:11 pm. It was also still on the shipping OS version. It did update to the latest OS version overnight, last night. I did not have any issues with overheating or needing to cooldown. Although I was not heavy on the laser projector. 

The "Look" feature is a cool hat trick and people are taken aback, when they hear it describe what it is seeing. Phone calls and music playback worked as expected. It did struggle with a couple of contacts that I requested to call. I think that is addressed in the latest update. Asking general questions of things that come to mind throughout the day, was cool. I liked that I could ask the question, get an answer and move on with my day.  It did feel warm off and on throughout the day, That probably has to do with when the booster is charging the Pin. The translation feature is spot on. I used it with a friend that speaks fluent Spanish, and he was impressed with the accuracy. When asking to take a picture there is about one beat too long before it starts to capture. I'm hoping that is addressed in future updates. I did notice my phone screen time was considerably down for the day, which is a big plus. 

Here is an outline of battery/booster usage for the day yesterday. 

Pin and booster on at 7:30 am, first booster swap at 11:35 am

Second booster swap at 1:03 pm

Third booster swap at 3:58 pm

Charged charge case for a bit at 3:58 pm

Fourth booster swap at 5:47 pm

Booster at 7% and Pin at 4% at 10:11 pm, put on charge for the night, along with charge case.

result.text:
Today we are announcing a new Project experience for @linear. For long, we've been focused on execution of issues and projects, but what comes before that is planning.

One of the key things about Linear is that it is always built with purpose and quality. Instead of throwing templates to teams to do their project management, we think about the needed workflows and create purpose built solutions for that.

In the project's case, it‚Äôs usually one where projects start in this vague state of some words on a page, and eventually grow, there is discussion, and it gets refined to something more specific. You start defining issues, and you can create them just highlighting text in the doc. Eventually the work starts and there will be milestones and project updates. Now this whole lifecycle this can happen in Linear.

Internally we moved all of our project specs, and product related documentation to Linear. The key thing we noticed is that this way the documentation is more accessible, accurate and authoritative for everyone. You don‚Äôt have random or multiple docs of the project, or you don‚Äôt have to hunt to find where the doc is. The doc is the project and Linear is where the project work actually happens.

This makes the experience with roadmaps and projects really seamless and fast. You can add your specs, research, meeting notes and all other information in the project. Once the project is done, all of this information gets archived together with the project and the docs don't linger around in different places.

Below see the experience narrated by our Head of Product @thenanyu. This year we will have more upcoming announcements around planning.

result.text:
Here are my thoughts and use of my @humane Pin for day four. I‚Äôd like to point out that I have never done anything like this before, as far as writing out my thoughts and uses of a product, to then share. As you can probably surmise, I am not a writer, a journalist, a reviewer, or anything close to that. I am aware of the overall length of my posts, and know they are as someone pointed out ‚Äúwayyyy to long‚Äù. I decided to do this as a discipline for me, to commit to something that takes me out of my comfort zone. So only a few more days of my daily ramblings‚Ä¶

Today I removed my Pin from charge and put it on at 7:45 am. I used the mic 45 times, made 1 phone call, played 54 songs, took 23 pictures, and made no translation requests. I am attaching a photo showing a few of the notes I have made, to tailor the Pin to my use. Today I also focused more on the booster battery usage. I discovered that when it announces ‚Äúbooster battery low‚Äù, that is when the booster as reached 10% remaining, which happened at 10:54 am. I decided to leave the booster battery on until it reached 0%, and requested that it let me know when it got to 0%. It responded with ‚ÄúA reminder has been set to notify you when the booster battery level reaches zero‚Äù. Not hearing anything for a bit, I checked the level again at 12:15 pm, it had reached 3% at that time. I continued on with my day, then thinking I missed an announcement, I checked again at 1:46 pm. The booster was still holding at 3%, the Pin during that time, had gone from 65% to 25%. It appears that once the booster reaches 3%, it will not deplete any further, which may be in place to preserver battery health. Then at 2:14 pm, the Pin announced again that the booster battery was low, and that the Pin was at 10%. I proceeded to change the booster battery at that time.

I took a trip to our local Lowe‚Äôs this morning to pick up a new garbage disposal for the kitchen sink. I paired the Pin with my other car, which want as smooth as it did pairing to the first car. Still no album data showing on the infotainment display. However, I was able to skip tracks and pause/resume music. I have been noticing a common theme when asking the Pin to play a particular album, this may relate to the Tidal service more than to the Pin. It will play the first song of the album, then skip around a few more songs from the album, then stop playing. I will tap the Pin to resume the music, but it continues playing the same last song from the beginning. While at Lowe‚Äôs I used the Pin to provide me with details and reviews about a few different garbage disposals. It summarized the reviews and provided highlights from the reviews. It also gave me a price range of the model and places to purchase.

I then went to pickup my son from our local sports center, where he was practicing basketball and playing a pickup game. This area is notorious for poor cell signal, no matter the carrier. I made a couple requests to take some pictures at 3:09 pm, it took two. It responded to the third command to take a picture, then struggled and gave the error tone. At 3:26 pm I got the rainbow bacon, and it appeared to reboot. I then entered my passcode to unlock via the laser projector. Then it announced that it was shutting down again, by the shutdown tone. It was not responding to touch or any attempts to wake it. A couple of times it would beacon a blue/green. At 3:37 pm it came back online, and worked as expected. Wore it while I mowed the lawn and took a few pictures, while mowing. At 4:46 pm the Pin notified me that the booster battery was at 9% audibly. Knowing I would be heading out for my son‚Äôs basketball game I decided to change the booster at 5:04 pm. I made a call to a friend at 5:19 for about four minutes. I used the Pin for audio, so no bluetooth devices. Call quality was clear on both ends. While out to dinner with the family, after a nail biter of a game, I asked the Pin the score of a live Astro‚Äôs game. It gave the correct score, but replied that the Astro‚Äôs had lost 0-3, the game was still in the 6th inning. However, they did end up losing, so maybe it can predict the future ;-). I ended the evening with the Pin going on charge at 10:43 pm. The Pin had 13% battery, and the booster 4% remaining.

result.text:
I made this last weekend to experiment w/ building an app end to end on LLMs: https://t.co/eOHZunKTyf

It's like Wirecutter, but uses an LLM to recommend product choices based on reddit conversations and reviews, so you don't have to spend 20-30min reading reddit

My experience: I'm late to the game, but this is the first time I've tried building an app end to end around an LLM.

1. It's very fast to build something that's 90% of a solution. The problem is that the last 10% of building something is usually the hard part which really matters, and with a black box at the center of the product, it feels much more difficult to me to nail that remaining 10%. With vibecheck, most of the time the results to my queries are great; some percentage of the time they aren't. Closing that gap with gen AI feels much more fickle to me than a normal engineering problem. It could be that I'm unfamiliar with it, but I also wonder if some classes of generative AI based products are just doomed to mediocrity as a result.

2. On the other hand, I think the discomfort I feel with having an unpredictable black box at the center of a product which can fail in very creative ways some percentage of the time might actually be a competitive advantage for startups. I think Wirecutter, especially branded as NY Times, would have a lot harder time tolerating that unpredictability and unreliability than an app like this (or an actual startup) which can set that product expectation with users to begin with. It might be that the current problems with generative AI are actually the things that create an innovator's dilemma and give startups an advantage to slip under the incumbents. It seems like the ideal spot right now would an app where 90% "done" is a mostly great experience, but the failings are still somehow not stomach-able by incumbents.

3. I do not understand how the economics of LLMs pencil out. When I look at the per concurrent user costs associated with inference, they seem orders of magnitude higher than per concurrent user costs of previous internet technologies. It seems to me that if previous apps like webmail, messengers, etc had costs as high, they would not have been viable products. This is something I want to learn more about.

result.text:
My daughter Sofia turns 2 soon‚Äînot so far away from entering the "why?" era‚Äîso this is an active question for me and @SoniaBaschez  

Many thoughts, some perhaps contradictory. Curious how other parents think about it.

1. I'm excited to teach Sofia everything I know about how the world works.

2. I'm excited to use AI to be able to learn answers to the "why" questions more quickly on the fly when she asks things I don't know.

3. As she gets older, I want Sofia to develop independence and learn to figure things out on her own, using all resources available.

4. As excited as I am today, I know there will be times when I'm busy or out of energy for "why?" questions. I don't think this makes me a bad parent. I think it makes me a good parent for showing her what we can realistically expect from other people in our lives.

5. I'm worried about the worldview AI will impart to Sofia. A lot of "why?" questions have answers that come down to values, and I would prefer for those values to be ours.

6. I'm worried about the effect an infinitely patient AI teacher/friend might have on Sofia's expectations of how other people will behave.

7. I'm less worried about the effect of talking to AI than I am about the effect of social media.

8. Inevitably, Sofia is going to encounter incorrect, biased, tasteless, and even abhorrent content. I don't know how we'll find the right balance between protection and exposure.

9. I'd like to be someone Sofia feels like she can talk to about anything she encounters, but then I think about how little I shared with my parents, and I have no idea what I'd do differently because tbh they were great.

10. There is no "right" answer, inevitably some parts of living in the future will be hard and bad, and that's a learning opportunity. Other parts will be amazing. We do the best we can with the information we have. As @paulg's mom put it, "all you have to do is love them and show them the world."

result.text:
Seb was right. We should've called pages: "pagelet.js" üê∑üòÇ

In Next.js, you can place shared UI inside `layout.js`. Layouts don't re-render on navigation, which reduces work on the server and the response size. But, this poses a challenge for UI that depends on URL changes.

Luckily, we can move logic into Client Components and use hooks like `usePathname` . These observe URL changes and respond instantly, without having to be refetched.

This approach works for simpler cases like active links. But what if you're trying to build UI that depends on both URL changes AND external data?  For example, breadcrumbs.

For cases like this, we can use parallel routes. By adding a slot, we can render both our main page and a parallel page.

Since pages re-render, both pagelets üê∑ üê∑ can respond to param changes and fetch updated data.

Layout(s) and pagelet(s) are rendered, cached and streamed independently and stitched back together on the client to form a complete page.
